{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MHT1nSyiZdZ3WMzTb77B6G","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→stepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4]\n     3→inputDocuments:\n     4→  - _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/tech-spec-rust-stack-support.md\n     5→  - _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd-operational-excellence.md\n     6→  - _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-operational-excellence.md\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→# Rust Stack Support - Epic Breakdown\n    10→\n    11→## Overview\n    12→\n    13→This document provides the complete epic and story breakdown for adding full Rust stack support to codeharness at parity with Node.js and Python.\n    14→\n    15→## Requirements Inventory\n    16→\n    17→### Functional Requirements\n    18→\n    19→FR1: System detects Rust projects via `Cargo.toml` presence and returns stack `'rust'`\n    20→FR2: System detects Rust app type (CLI, server, library, agent, generic) by parsing `Cargo.toml` sections and dependencies\n    21→FR3: System detects `[workspace]` projects and treats them as single projects with `--workspace` flags\n    22→FR4: System generates multi-stage Dockerfile for Rust projects (build + runtime stages)\n    23→FR5: System installs OTLP crates (`opentelemetry`, `opentelemetry-otlp`, `tracing-opentelemetry`, `tracing-subscriber`) via `cargo add`\n    24→FR6: System provides LLM guidance doc for Rust OTLP instrumentation (`templates/otlp/rust.md`)\n    25→FR7: System detects `cargo-tarpaulin` as coverage tool for Rust projects\n    26→FR8: System parses `tarpaulin-report.json` for coverage percentage\n    27→FR9: System parses `cargo test` output for pass/fail counts\n    28→FR10: System generates AGENTS.md with Rust build/test commands\n    29→FR11: System creates Semgrep rules for Rust observability patterns (`tracing` crate)\n    30→FR12: System creates verification Dockerfile for Rust projects\n    31→FR13: System registers `cargo-tarpaulin` in dependency registry\n    32→FR14: System expands state types to support Rust coverage tool and OTLP config\n    33→\n    34→### NonFunctional Requirements\n    35→\n    36→NFR1: No file exceeds 300 lines (existing constraint from architecture)\n    37→NFR2: All new code has unit tests — 0 regressions on existing tests\n    38→NFR3: No new npm dependencies added to codeharness itself\n    39→NFR4: Cargo.toml parsing uses simple string matching — no TOML parser dependency\n    40→NFR5: All changes follow existing Result<T> pattern and module boundaries\n    41→\n    42→### Additional Requirements\n    43→\n    44→- Workspace detection must not break single-crate projects (false positive guard)\n    45→- `cargo-tarpaulin` is runtime-only dependency — not required at codeharness build time\n    46→- Semgrep Rust rules target standard `tracing` crate patterns only (custom macros out of scope)\n    47→- Verification Dockerfile needs Python for Semgrep even in Rust projects\n    48→\n    49→### FR Coverage Map\n    50→\n    51→| FR | Epic | Story |\n    52→|----|------|-------|\n    53→| FR1, FR2, FR3 | Epic 1 | 8-1 |\n    54→| FR14 | Epic 1 | 8-2 |\n    55→| FR7, FR8, FR9 | Epic 2 | 8-3 |\n    56→| FR13 | Epic 2 | 8-4 |\n    57→| FR4 | Epic 3 | 8-5 |\n    58→| FR12 | Epic 3 | 8-6 |\n    59→| FR5, FR6 | Epic 4 | 8-7 |\n    60→| FR10 | Epic 4 | 8-8 |\n    61→| FR11 | Epic 5 | 8-9 |\n    62→\n    63→## Epic List\n    64→\n    65→- **Epic 1: Rust Detection Foundation** — Stack detection, app type detection, state type expansion\n    66→- **Epic 2: Rust Coverage & Testing** — cargo-tarpaulin detection, report parsing, test output parsing\n    67→- **Epic 3: Rust Infrastructure** — Dockerfile template, verification Dockerfile\n    68→- **Epic 4: Rust Observability & Docs** — OTLP instrumentation, guidance doc, docs scaffolding\n    69→- **Epic 5: Rust Static Analysis** — Semgrep rules for tracing patterns\n    70→\n    71→## Epic 1: Rust Detection Foundation\n    72→\n    73→Enable codeharness to recognize Rust projects, detect their type, and store Rust-specific state.\n    74→\n    75→### Story 8-1: Rust stack and app type detection\n    76→\n    77→As a developer initializing codeharness on a Rust project,\n    78→I want the harness to detect my project as Rust and identify whether it's a CLI, server, library, or agent,\n    79→So that all downstream features (coverage, OTLP, Dockerfile) use the correct Rust configuration.\n    80→\n    81→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    82→\n    83→**Given** a directory contains `Cargo.toml`\n    84→**When** `detectStack()` is called\n    85→**Then** it returns `'rust'`\n    86→\n    87→**Given** a Rust project with `[[bin]]` in Cargo.toml and no web framework deps\n    88→**When** `detectAppType()` is called\n    89→**Then** it returns `'cli'`\n    90→\n    91→**Given** a Rust project with `axum` in `[dependencies]`\n    92→**When** `detectAppType()` is called\n    93→**Then** it returns `'server'`\n    94→\n    95→**Given** a Rust project with `[lib]` section and no `[[bin]]`\n    96→**When** `detectAppType()` is called\n    97→**Then** it returns `'generic'` (library)\n    98→\n    99→**Given** a Rust project with `async-openai` in dependencies\n   100→**When** `detectAppType()` is called\n   101→**Then** it returns `'agent'`\n   102→\n   103→**Given** a Rust project with `[workspace]` in Cargo.toml\n   104→**When** `detectStack()` is called\n   105→**Then** it still returns `'rust'` (treated as single project)\n   106→\n   107→**Given** no `Cargo.toml` exists\n   108→**When** `detectStack()` is called\n   109→**Then** Rust is NOT detected (no false positive)\n   110→\n   111→### Story 8-2: Expand state types for Rust\n   112→\n   113→As a developer,\n   114→I want the harness state to support Rust-specific fields,\n   115→So that coverage tool and OTLP config are correctly stored.\n   116→\n   117→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   118→\n   119→**Given** a Rust project is initialized\n   120→**When** state is written\n   121→**Then** `coverage.tool` accepts `'cargo-tarpaulin'` without type errors\n   122→\n   123→**Given** a Rust project has OTLP configured\n   124→**When** state is written\n   125→**Then** `otlp.rust_env_hint` field is present with value `'OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT'`\n   126→\n   127→## Epic 2: Rust Coverage & Testing\n   128→\n   129→Enable coverage detection, report parsing, and test output parsing for Rust projects using cargo-tarpaulin.\n   130→\n   131→### Story 8-3: cargo-tarpaulin coverage detection and parsing\n   132→\n   133→As a developer running coverage on a Rust project,\n   134→I want codeharness to detect cargo-tarpaulin, run it, and parse the JSON report,\n   135→So that coverage metrics are tracked at parity with Node.js/Python.\n   136→\n   137→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   138→\n   139→**Given** a Rust project with `cargo-tarpaulin` installed\n   140→**When** `detectCoverageTool()` is called\n   141→**Then** it returns `{ tool: 'cargo-tarpaulin', runCommand: 'cargo tarpaulin --out json --output-dir coverage/', reportFormat: 'tarpaulin-json' }`\n   142→\n   143→**Given** a Rust workspace project\n   144→**When** `detectCoverageTool()` is called\n   145→**Then** the run command includes `--workspace` flag\n   146→\n   147→**Given** a `coverage/tarpaulin-report.json` file with `\"coverage\": 85.5`\n   148→**When** `parseCoverageReport()` is called with format `'tarpaulin-json'`\n   149→**Then** it returns `85.5`\n   150→\n   151→**Given** `cargo test` output containing `test result: ok. 42 passed; 3 failed; 0 ignored`\n   152→**When** `parseTestCounts()` is called\n   153→**Then** it returns `{ passCount: 42, failCount: 3 }`\n   154→\n   155→**Given** `cargo-tarpaulin` is NOT installed\n   156→**When** `detectCoverageTool()` is called on a Rust project\n   157→**Then** it returns `{ tool: 'unknown' }` with a warning\n   158→\n   159→### Story 8-4: Register cargo-tarpaulin in dependency registry\n   160→\n   161→As a developer initializing codeharness on a Rust project,\n   162→I want cargo-tarpaulin to be auto-installed if missing,\n   163→So that coverage works out of the box.\n   164→\n   165→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   166→\n   167→**Given** `cargo-tarpaulin` is not installed\n   168→**When** `codeharness init` runs on a Rust project\n   169→**Then** it attempts `cargo install cargo-tarpaulin`\n   170→\n   171→**Given** the dependency registry\n   172→**When** checked for `cargo-tarpaulin`\n   173→**Then** it has `critical: false`, install command `cargo install cargo-tarpaulin`, check command `cargo tarpaulin --version`\n   174→\n   175→## Epic 3: Rust Infrastructure\n   176→\n   177→Generate Dockerfiles for Rust project deployment and verification.\n   178→\n   179→### Story 8-5: Rust Dockerfile template generation\n   180→\n   181→As a developer deploying a Rust project,\n   182→I want codeharness to generate a multi-stage Dockerfile,\n   183→So that I get a minimal runtime image with just the compiled binary.\n   184→\n   185→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   186→\n   187→**Given** a Rust project without a Dockerfile\n   188→**When** `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called\n   189→**Then** it writes a multi-stage Dockerfile with `rust:1.82-slim` builder and `debian:bookworm-slim` runtime\n   190→\n   191→**Given** the generated Dockerfile\n   192→**When** inspected\n   193→**Then** it includes `cargo build --release` in build stage, `curl`/`jq` in runtime stage, and runs as non-root user\n   194→\n   195→**Given** a Rust project with an existing Dockerfile\n   196→**When** `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called\n   197→**Then** it returns `fail('Dockerfile already exists')`\n   198→\n   199→### Story 8-6: Rust verification Dockerfile\n   200→\n   201→As a developer verifying a Rust project,\n   202→I want a verification environment with Rust tooling, Semgrep, and showboat,\n   203→So that automated verification works for Rust projects.\n   204→\n   205→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   206→\n   207→**Given** `templates/Dockerfile.verify.rust` exists\n   208→**When** built\n   209→**Then** it includes `rust:1.82-slim`, Python + Semgrep, showboat, cargo-tarpaulin, curl, jq\n   210→\n   211→**Given** the verification Dockerfile\n   212→**When** inspected\n   213→**Then** OTLP environment variables are configured pointing to host Docker endpoint\n   214→\n   215→## Epic 4: Rust Observability & Documentation\n   216→\n   217→Add OTLP instrumentation support and documentation scaffolding for Rust projects.\n   218→\n   219→### Story 8-7: Rust OTLP instrumentation\n   220→\n   221→As a developer instrumenting a Rust project,\n   222→I want codeharness to add OpenTelemetry crates and provide setup guidance,\n   223→So that I can quickly enable observability.\n   224→\n   225→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   226→\n   227→**Given** a Rust project\n   228→**When** `instrumentProject()` runs\n   229→**Then** `cargo add opentelemetry opentelemetry-otlp tracing-opentelemetry tracing-subscriber` is executed\n   230→\n   231→**Given** OTLP instrumentation succeeds\n   232→**When** state is updated\n   233→**Then** `configureOtlpEnvVars()` writes `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` and `OTEL_SERVICE_NAME` to `.env.codeharness`\n   234→\n   235→**Given** a Rust project\n   236→**When** `configureAgent()` is called\n   237→**Then** it skips with info message (no standard Rust agent SDK yet)\n   238→\n   239→**Given** `templates/otlp/rust.md` exists\n   240→**When** read\n   241→**Then** it contains: packages to add, `tracing_subscriber` setup code snippet, `#[tracing::instrument]` usage, env vars, verification steps\n   242→\n   243→### Story 8-8: Rust documentation scaffolding\n   244→\n   245→As a developer initializing a Rust project,\n   246→I want AGENTS.md to include Rust-specific build/test commands,\n   247→So that AI agents know how to build and test my project.\n   248→\n   249→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   250→\n   251→**Given** a Rust project\n   252→**When** `getStackLabel()` is called\n   253→**Then** it returns `'Rust (Cargo.toml)'`\n   254→\n   255→**Given** a Rust project\n   256→**When** `getCoverageTool()` is called\n   257→**Then** it returns `'cargo-tarpaulin'`\n   258→\n   259→**Given** a Rust project\n   260→**When** `generateAgentsMdContent()` is called\n   261→**Then** output includes `cargo build`, `cargo test`, `cargo tarpaulin --out json`\n   262→\n   263→**Given** a Rust project with `[package] name = \"myapp\"` in Cargo.toml\n   264→**When** `getProjectName()` is called\n   265→**Then** it returns `'myapp'` (reads from Cargo.toml, not package.json)\n   266→\n   267→## Epic 5: Rust Static Analysis\n   268→\n   269→Create Semgrep rules to detect observability gaps in Rust code using tracing crate patterns.\n   270→\n   271→### Story 8-9: Semgrep rules for Rust observability\n   272→\n   273→As a developer auditing a Rust project,\n   274→I want Semgrep to detect functions and error paths without tracing,\n   275→So that observability gaps are identified automatically.\n   276→\n   277→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   278→\n   279→**Given** a Rust function without `tracing::debug!`, `tracing::info!`, or `#[instrument]`\n   280→**When** Semgrep runs with `rust-function-no-tracing` rule\n   281→**Then** it reports an observability gap\n   282→\n   283→**Given** a Rust `match` arm handling `Err` without `tracing::error!` or `tracing::warn!`\n   284→**When** Semgrep runs with `rust-catch-without-tracing` rule\n   285→**Then** it reports an observability gap\n   286→\n   287→**Given** a Rust `.map_err()` or `.unwrap_or_else()` closure without tracing macros\n   288→**When** Semgrep runs with `rust-error-path-no-tracing` rule\n   289→**Then** it reports an observability gap\n   290→\n   291→**Given** all 3 Rust rule files in `patches/observability/`\n   292→**When** `codeharness audit` runs on a Rust project with Semgrep installed\n   293→**Then** the observability static analysis dimension uses the Rust rules automatically (Semgrep auto-discovers by `languages: [rust]`)\n   294→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0171dfRPdau3d9vdSdBsjERK","session_id":"8e4c6a49-a8f5-4820-a234-101957ee0803","uuid":"88d8a017-9006-4ac5-966d-21132b64673c","timestamp":"2026-03-23T07:33:51.131Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Ukek7zHu5yJAyu7CSLuCDK","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→title: 'Full Rust Stack Support'\n     3→slug: 'rust-stack-support'\n     4→created: '2026-03-23'\n     5→status: 'ready-for-dev'\n     6→stepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4]\n     7→tech_stack: ['typescript', 'rust', 'vitest', 'semgrep']\n     8→files_to_modify:\n     9→  - src/lib/stack-detect.ts\n    10→  - src/lib/otlp.ts\n    11→  - src/lib/coverage.ts\n    12→  - src/lib/state.ts\n    13→  - src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts\n    14→  - src/modules/infra/docs-scaffold.ts\n    15→  - src/commands/init.ts\n    16→  - src/modules/infra/init-project.ts\n    17→  - src/modules/observability/analyzer.ts\n    18→  - src/lib/deps.ts\n    19→files_to_create:\n    20→  - templates/otlp/rust.md\n    21→  - templates/Dockerfile.verify.rust\n    22→  - patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml\n    23→  - patches/observability/rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml\n    24→  - patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml\n    25→code_patterns:\n    26→  - 'if/else on stack === \"nodejs\" | \"python\" — add \"rust\" branch at each'\n    27→  - 'Per-stack install/patch/detect functions: installNodeOtlp(), installPythonOtlp() → add installRustOtlp()'\n    28→  - 'Cargo.toml TOML parsing for app type and dependency detection'\n    29→test_patterns:\n    30→  - 'Mirror existing stack-detect.test.ts patterns for Rust cases'\n    31→  - 'Mirror otlp.test.ts patterns with Cargo.toml fixtures'\n    32→  - 'Mirror coverage.test.ts patterns with tarpaulin JSON fixtures'\n    33→---\n    34→\n    35→# Tech-Spec: Full Rust Stack Support\n    36→\n    37→**Created:** 2026-03-23\n    38→\n    39→## Overview\n    40→\n    41→### Problem Statement\n    42→\n    43→Codeharness supports Node.js and Python across stack detection, OTLP instrumentation, coverage tools, Dockerfile generation, Semgrep rules, and docs scaffolding. Rust projects get `null` stack and no harness features. ~25 language-conditional code paths need Rust branches.\n    44→\n    45→### Solution\n    46→\n    47→Add Rust as a first-class stack at parity with TypeScript/Python. Use `cargo-tarpaulin` for coverage, `opentelemetry`/`opentelemetry-otlp` crates for OTLP, basic scaffolding + LLM guidance for instrumentation, and Semgrep Rust rules for observability static analysis. Treat workspaces (`[workspace]`) as single projects.\n    48→\n    49→### Scope\n    50→\n    51→**In Scope:**\n    52→- Stack detection (`Cargo.toml`, `[workspace]` support)\n    53→- App type detection (CLI/library/server via Cargo.toml parsing)\n    54→- Dockerfile generation (`rustTemplate()`)\n    55→- Verification Dockerfile (`Dockerfile.verify.rust`)\n    56→- OTLP dependency addition + config + LLM guidance docs\n    57→- Coverage tool detection (`cargo-tarpaulin`)\n    58→- Coverage report parsing (tarpaulin JSON format)\n    59→- Semgrep rules for Rust observability patterns\n    60→- Docs scaffolding (AGENTS.md, build commands)\n    61→- State file support (`rust` stack, `cargo-tarpaulin` tool)\n    62→- Tests for all new code paths\n    63→\n    64→**Out of Scope:**\n    65→- Full auto-instrumentation code generation (LLM handles this via guidance docs)\n    66→- Per-crate workspace enumeration (treat workspace as single project)\n    67→- New observability backends\n    68→- Custom verification strategies\n    69→\n    70→## Context for Development\n    71→\n    72→### Codebase Patterns\n    73→\n    74→- All stack-conditional logic uses `if (stack === 'nodejs') { ... } else if (stack === 'python') { ... }` — add `else if (stack === 'rust') { ... }` at each location\n    75→- Per-stack functions follow naming convention: `installNodeOtlp()`, `installPythonOtlp()` → add `installRustOtlp()`\n    76→- Coverage detection follows: `detectNodeCoverageTool()`, `detectPythonCoverageTool()` → add `detectRustCoverageTool()`\n    77→- Dockerfile templates follow: `nodejsTemplate()`, `pythonTemplate()` → add `rustTemplate()`\n    78→- OTLP templates are static markdown files in `templates/otlp/{stack}.md`\n    79→- Tests mirror source structure: `src/lib/__tests__/`, `src/modules/infra/__tests__/`\n    80→\n    81→### Files to Reference\n    82→\n    83→| File | Purpose | Lines | Rust Touchpoints |\n    84→| ---- | ------- | ----- | ---------------- |\n    85→| `src/lib/stack-detect.ts` | Stack detection + app type detection | 146 | `detectStack()` L7-14, `detectAppType()` L72-145, add Rust dep constants |\n    86→| `src/lib/otlp.ts` | OTLP instrumentation per stack | ~330 | `installRustOtlp()` new fn, `instrumentProject()` L295, `configureOtlpEnvVars()` L258-274, `configureAgent()` L207-227 |\n    87→| `src/lib/coverage.ts` | Coverage tool detection + report parsing | ~400 | `detectCoverageTool()` L35-53, `detectRustCoverageTool()` new fn, `parseTarpaulinCoverage()` new fn, `parseCoverageReport()` L257, `parseTestCounts()` L308 add cargo test format, `CoverageToolInfo.tool` type union |\n    88→| `src/lib/state.ts` | HarnessState interface | — | `coverage.tool` type, `otlp.rust_env_hint` field |\n    89→| `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` | Dockerfile generation per stack | 119 | `rustTemplate()` new fn, `generateDockerfileTemplate()` L99-108 |\n    90→| `src/modules/infra/docs-scaffold.ts` | AGENTS.md + docs generation | 197 | `getStackLabel()` L32-36, `getCoverageTool()` L38-41, `generateAgentsMdContent()` L43-98 |\n    91→| `src/modules/observability/analyzer.ts` | Semgrep static analysis runner | ~150 | No code changes — Semgrep auto-discovers `.yaml` rules by language |\n    92→| `src/lib/deps.ts` | Dependency registry | ~100 | Add `cargo-tarpaulin` to `DEPENDENCY_REGISTRY` |\n    93→| `patches/observability/*.yaml` | Semgrep rules (JS/TS) | 3 files | Create 3 new Rust-specific YAML rules |\n    94→| `templates/otlp/nodejs.md` | Node.js OTLP guide | 54 | Pattern for `templates/otlp/rust.md` |\n    95→| `templates/otlp/python.md` | Python OTLP guide | 52 | Pattern for `templates/otlp/rust.md` |\n    96→| `templates/Dockerfile.verify` | Node.js verification Dockerfile | — | Pattern for `templates/Dockerfile.verify.rust` |\n    97→\n    98→### Technical Decisions\n    99→\n   100→- **Cargo.toml parsing:** Use `readTextSafe()` (already in stack-detect.ts) + simple string matching / regex on TOML content. No TOML parser dependency. Check for `[workspace]`, `[[bin]]`, `[lib]`, and known framework deps in `[dependencies]`.\n   101→- **Workspace handling:** Treat as single project. Use `--workspace` flag for `cargo test` and `cargo tarpaulin`. Detect via `[workspace]` section in root `Cargo.toml`.\n   102→- **OTLP approach:** Add `opentelemetry` + `opentelemetry-otlp` + `tracing-opentelemetry` crates via `cargo add`. Provide LLM guidance doc (`templates/otlp/rust.md`) explaining how to wire up `tracing` subscriber with OTLP exporter layer. Basic scaffolding only — LLM handles actual instrumentation.\n   103→- **Coverage:** `cargo-tarpaulin` with `--out Json` output. Parse `tarpaulin-report.json` for line coverage. Tarpaulin JSON format: `{ \"files\": [...], \"coverage\": 85.5 }` — top-level `coverage` field is the overall percentage.\n   104→- **Semgrep Rust rules:** Create 3 rules in `patches/observability/` with `languages: [rust]`:\n   105→  - `rust-function-no-tracing.yaml` — functions without `tracing::debug!`/`tracing::info!`/`#[instrument]`\n   106→  - `rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml` — `Err` match arms without `tracing::error!`/`tracing::warn!`\n   107→  - `rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml` — `.unwrap_or_else`/`.map_err` without tracing\n   108→- **Dockerfile base:** Multi-stage build. Build stage: `rust:1.82-slim`, compile with `cargo build --release`. Runtime stage: `debian:bookworm-slim`, copy binary only. Add `curl`, `jq` for verification.\n   109→- **CoverageToolInfo type expansion:** Change `tool: 'c8' | 'coverage.py' | 'unknown'` to `tool: 'c8' | 'coverage.py' | 'cargo-tarpaulin' | 'unknown'`.\n   110→- **Rust app type detection constants:**\n   111→  - `RUST_WEB_FRAMEWORKS = ['actix-web', 'axum', 'rocket', 'tide', 'warp']`\n   112→  - `RUST_AGENT_DEPS = ['async-openai', 'anthropic', 'llm-chain']`\n   113→  - Detect CLI: `[[bin]]` without web framework deps\n   114→  - Detect library: `[lib]` section present, no `[[bin]]`\n   115→  - Detect server: web framework dep present\n   116→- **cargo-tarpaulin in dependency registry:** Add to `DEPENDENCY_REGISTRY` in `deps.ts` with `cargo install cargo-tarpaulin` as install command, `cargo tarpaulin --version` as check command, `critical: false`.\n   117→- **Test output parsing:** `cargo test` output format: `test result: ok. 42 passed; 0 failed; 0 ignored` — add regex to `parseTestCounts()`.\n   118→\n   119→## Implementation Plan\n   120→\n   121→### Tasks\n   122→\n   123→Tasks ordered by dependency — foundation first, then consumers.\n   124→\n   125→- [ ] Task 1: Stack detection — add Rust to `detectStack()` and `detectAppType()`\n   126→  - File: `src/lib/stack-detect.ts`\n   127→  - Action: Add `if (existsSync(join(dir, 'Cargo.toml'))) return 'rust';` after Python checks in `detectStack()` (L11). Add Rust constants `RUST_WEB_FRAMEWORKS`, `RUST_AGENT_DEPS`. Add `if (stack === 'rust') { ... }` block in `detectAppType()` after Python block (L142). Implement `getCargoContent()` helper using `readTextSafe()`. Parse `Cargo.toml` text for `[[bin]]`, `[lib]`, `[workspace]`, and dependency names. Priority order: agent → server (web framework) → CLI (`[[bin]]`) → library (`[lib]`) → generic.\n   128→  - Notes: Use `readTextSafe()` already in file. Simple string matching for TOML sections — no TOML parser. For `[workspace]` projects, still return the detected app type based on root deps.\n   129→\n   130→- [ ] Task 2: Coverage tool detection — add `cargo-tarpaulin`\n   131→  - File: `src/lib/coverage.ts`\n   132→  - Action: Expand `CoverageToolInfo.tool` type union to include `'cargo-tarpaulin'`. Add `if (stack === 'rust') { return detectRustCoverageTool(baseDir); }` in `detectCoverageTool()` (L47). Create `detectRustCoverageTool()` — check for `Cargo.toml`, check if `cargo-tarpaulin` is present (try `cargo tarpaulin --version`), return `{ tool: 'cargo-tarpaulin', runCommand: 'cargo tarpaulin --out json --output-dir coverage/', reportFormat: 'tarpaulin-json' }`. For workspace projects, add `--workspace` flag. Create `parseTarpaulinCoverage()` — read `coverage/tarpaulin-report.json`, extract top-level `coverage` field (float 0-100). Add `'tarpaulin-json'` case to `parseCoverageReport()`. Add `cargo test` regex to `parseTestCounts()`: `/test result: ok\\. (\\d+) passed; (\\d+) failed/`.\n   133→  - Notes: Detect workspace by checking `Cargo.toml` for `[workspace]`. If tarpaulin not installed, return `tool: 'unknown'` with warning.\n   134→\n   135→- [ ] Task 3: Dockerfile template — add `rustTemplate()`\n   136→  - File: `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts`\n   137→  - Action: Create `rustTemplate()` function returning multi-stage Dockerfile string. Build stage: `FROM rust:1.82-slim AS builder`, `WORKDIR /build`, `COPY . .`, `RUN cargo build --release`. Runtime stage: `FROM debian:bookworm-slim`, `RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends curl jq && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*`, `COPY --from=builder /build/target/release/<binary> /usr/local/bin/`, `USER nobody`, `WORKDIR /workspace`. Add `else if (stack === 'rust')` in `generateDockerfileTemplate()` (L102).\n   138→  - Notes: Use `<binary>` placeholder — user must replace with their binary name. Add comment in template.\n   139→\n   140→- [ ] Task 4: OTLP instrumentation — add Rust support\n   141→  - File: `src/lib/otlp.ts`\n   142→  - Action: Add `RUST_OTLP_PACKAGES = ['opentelemetry', 'opentelemetry-otlp', 'tracing-opentelemetry', 'tracing-subscriber']`. Create `installRustOtlp()` — runs `cargo add` for each package. Add `else if (stack === 'rust')` in `instrumentProject()` (L309). In `configureOtlpEnvVars()` (L268), add Rust case: `{ rust_env_hint: 'OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT' }` to state. In `configureAgent()` (L207), add Rust case — no standard agent SDK for Rust yet, so skip with info message.\n   143→  - Notes: `cargo add` adds to `Cargo.toml [dependencies]`. Must run from project root. If `cargo add` fails (not in a cargo project), return failed status.\n   144→\n   145→- [ ] Task 5: OTLP guidance doc — create `templates/otlp/rust.md`\n   146→  - File: `templates/otlp/rust.md` (new)\n   147→  - Action: Create LLM guidance doc following pattern of `nodejs.md`/`python.md`. Include: packages to add (`cargo add ...`), code snippet for setting up `tracing_subscriber` with OTLP layer in `main.rs`, `#[tracing::instrument]` attribute usage for functions, environment variables (same as Node/Python: `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT`, `OTEL_SERVICE_NAME`), verification steps.\n   148→  - Notes: This is guidance for the LLM, not auto-generated code. Keep it concise and practical.\n   149→\n   150→- [ ] Task 6: Docs scaffolding — add Rust to AGENTS.md and labels\n   151→  - File: `src/modules/infra/docs-scaffold.ts`\n   152→  - Action: Add `if (stack === 'rust') return 'Rust (Cargo.toml)';` in `getStackLabel()` (L34). Add `if (stack === 'rust') return 'cargo-tarpaulin';` in `getCoverageTool()` (L40). Add Rust case in `generateAgentsMdContent()` (L66): `cargo build`, `cargo test`, `cargo tarpaulin --out json`. Update `getProjectName()` to read `[package] name = \"...\"` from `Cargo.toml` if no `package.json`.\n   153→  - Notes: `getProjectName()` currently only reads `package.json`. For Rust, parse `Cargo.toml` for `name = \"...\"` in `[package]` section.\n   154→\n   155→- [ ] Task 7: Dependency registry — add `cargo-tarpaulin`\n   156→  - File: `src/lib/deps.ts`\n   157→  - Action: Add to `DEPENDENCY_REGISTRY`: `{ name: 'cargo-tarpaulin', displayName: 'cargo-tarpaulin', installCommands: [{ cmd: 'cargo', args: ['install', 'cargo-tarpaulin'] }], checkCommand: { cmd: 'cargo', args: ['tarpaulin', '--version'] }, critical: false }`.\n   158→  - Notes: Only relevant for Rust projects. The init pipeline should only install this for Rust stacks.\n   159→\n   160→- [ ] Task 8: Semgrep rules — create Rust observability rules\n   161→  - Files: `patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml`, `rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml`, `rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml` (all new)\n   162→  - Action: Create 3 Semgrep YAML rules with `languages: [rust]`. Rule 1: functions without `tracing::debug!`/`tracing::info!`/`#[instrument]`. Rule 2: `Err(...)` match arms without `tracing::error!`/`tracing::warn!`. Rule 3: `.map_err()`/`.unwrap_or_else()` closures without tracing macros. Follow structure of existing JS/TS rules.\n   163→  - Notes: Semgrep's Rust support is solid for pattern matching. The analyzer module auto-discovers rules by scanning `patches/observability/` — no code changes needed in `analyzer.ts`.\n   164→\n   165→- [ ] Task 9: Verification Dockerfile — create Rust variant\n   166→  - File: `templates/Dockerfile.verify.rust` (new)\n   167→  - Action: Create verification environment Dockerfile for Rust projects. Base: `rust:1.82-slim`. Install: Python + pipx + Semgrep (for static analysis), showboat (for proof docs), curl + jq. Configure OTLP env vars. Install `cargo-tarpaulin`. Pattern: follow existing `Dockerfile.verify` but replace Node.js tooling with Rust tooling.\n   168→  - Notes: Semgrep requires Python, so Python is needed even in Rust verification images.\n   169→\n   170→- [ ] Task 10: State type — expand for Rust\n   171→  - File: `src/lib/state.ts`\n   172→  - Action: Ensure `HarnessState.coverage.tool` type accepts `'cargo-tarpaulin'`. Add optional `rust_env_hint?: string` to OTLP state section. No breaking changes — all additions are optional fields.\n   173→  - Notes: Minimal change. The state file is YAML frontmatter in `.claude/codeharness.local.md`.\n   174→\n   175→- [ ] Task 11: Tests — full coverage for all new code\n   176→  - Files: `src/lib/__tests__/stack-detect.test.ts`, `src/lib/__tests__/coverage.test.ts`, `src/lib/__tests__/otlp.test.ts`, `src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-template.test.ts`, `src/modules/infra/__tests__/docs-scaffold.test.ts`, `src/lib/__tests__/deps.test.ts`\n   177→  - Action: Add Rust test cases mirroring existing Node.js/Python patterns. Stack detection: `Cargo.toml` exists → returns `'rust'`, workspace detection, app type detection (CLI/server/library/agent). Coverage: tarpaulin detection, tarpaulin JSON parsing, workspace `--workspace` flag, `cargo test` output parsing. OTLP: `installRustOtlp()` success/failure, env var config. Dockerfile: `rustTemplate()` content, multi-stage build. Docs: stack label, coverage tool name, build commands. Deps: cargo-tarpaulin registry entry.\n   178→  - Notes: Use `vi.mock('node:fs')` and `vi.mock('node:child_process')` patterns from existing tests. Create `Cargo.toml` fixtures with various configurations.\n   179→\n   180→### Acceptance Criteria\n   181→\n   182→- [ ] AC1: Given a project with `Cargo.toml`, when `codeharness init` runs, then stack is detected as `'rust'` and displayed as `Rust (Cargo.toml)`\n   183→- [ ] AC2: Given a Rust project with `[[bin]]` in Cargo.toml, when `detectAppType()` is called, then it returns `'cli'`\n   184→- [ ] AC3: Given a Rust project with `axum` in dependencies, when `detectAppType()` is called, then it returns `'server'`\n   185→- [ ] AC4: Given a Rust project with `[workspace]` in Cargo.toml, when coverage runs, then `--workspace` flag is included in the tarpaulin command\n   186→- [ ] AC5: Given a Rust project, when `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called, then it produces a multi-stage Dockerfile with `rust:1.82-slim` builder and `debian:bookworm-slim` runtime\n   187→- [ ] AC6: Given a Rust project, when OTLP instrumentation runs, then `cargo add opentelemetry opentelemetry-otlp tracing-opentelemetry tracing-subscriber` is executed\n   188→- [ ] AC7: Given a Rust project with `cargo-tarpaulin` installed, when `detectCoverageTool()` is called, then it returns `{ tool: 'cargo-tarpaulin', runCommand: 'cargo tarpaulin ...', reportFormat: 'tarpaulin-json' }`\n   189→- [ ] AC8: Given a `tarpaulin-report.json` file with `\"coverage\": 85.5`, when `parseCoverageReport()` is called, then it returns `85.5`\n   190→- [ ] AC9: Given `cargo test` output `test result: ok. 42 passed; 3 failed; 0 ignored`, when `parseTestCounts()` is called, then it returns `{ passCount: 42, failCount: 3 }`\n   191→- [ ] AC10: Given a Rust project, when `generateAgentsMdContent()` is called, then it includes `cargo build`, `cargo test`, and `cargo tarpaulin` commands\n   192→- [ ] AC11: Given Semgrep is installed, when observability analysis runs on a Rust project, then `rust-function-no-tracing` rule detects functions without tracing\n   193→- [ ] AC12: Given a Rust project, when docs scaffolding runs, then `getCoverageTool()` returns `'cargo-tarpaulin'` and `getStackLabel()` returns `'Rust (Cargo.toml)'`\n   194→- [ ] AC13: Given no `Cargo.toml` exists, when `detectStack()` runs, then Rust is NOT detected (no false positives)\n   195→- [ ] AC14: Given all Rust features are implemented, when `npm test` runs, then all existing tests pass with 0 regressions and new Rust tests pass\n   196→\n   197→## Additional Context\n   198→\n   199→### Dependencies\n   200→\n   201→- **cargo-tarpaulin**: Must be installable via `cargo install cargo-tarpaulin` on the target machine. Not required at codeharness build time — only at runtime on Rust projects.\n   202→- **Semgrep Rust support**: Semgrep supports Rust natively. No additional plugins needed. Rules use `languages: [rust]`.\n   203→- **No new npm dependencies**: All changes are internal to existing modules. No new packages added to codeharness itself.\n   204→\n   205→### Testing Strategy\n   206→\n   207→- **Unit tests**: Mock `fs.existsSync`, `fs.readFileSync`, `child_process.execFileSync` to simulate Rust project structures. Create `Cargo.toml` content fixtures for: plain binary, library, workspace, web framework project, agent project.\n   208→- **Integration tests**: None required — the init pipeline integration is already tested generically. Adding Rust to existing integration patterns is sufficient.\n   209→- **Manual testing**: Run `codeharness init` in a real Rust project (e.g., `cargo new test-project`) and verify all features work end-to-end.\n   210→- **Regression safety**: Run full test suite (`npm test`) after each task to catch breakage immediately. Target: 0 regressions.\n   211→\n   212→### Notes\n   213→\n   214→- **Cargo.toml parsing is intentionally simple**: Using regex/string matching avoids adding a TOML parser dependency. This works for the patterns we need (`[[bin]]`, `[lib]`, `[workspace]`, dependency names). If more complex parsing is needed later, consider adding the `toml` npm package.\n   215→- **No auto-instrumentation for Rust**: Unlike Node.js (auto-instrumentation via `--require`) and Python (`opentelemetry-instrument` wrapper), Rust requires explicit code changes to set up tracing. The guidance doc in `templates/otlp/rust.md` gives the LLM what it needs to instrument the project.\n   216→- **Semgrep Rust rule quality**: Rust's macro system means Semgrep patterns may not catch all tracing variants (e.g., custom macros wrapping `tracing`). The rules cover standard `tracing` crate patterns. Custom macros are out of scope.\n   217→- **Future consideration**: Go and Java support would follow the same pattern. The architecture is now proven for 3 languages.\n   218→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0171dfRPdau3d9vdSdBsjERK","session_id":"8e4c6a49-a8f5-4820-a234-101957ee0803","uuid":"61936bf2-c122-41be-a213-d0fc591e426a","timestamp":"2026-03-23T07:33:51.298Z"}
