{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01ShYGgyVheJkafUki7CwdQ2","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 8.5: Rust Dockerfile template generation\n     2→\n     3→Status: verifying\n     4→\n     5→<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n     6→\n     7→## Story\n     8→\n     9→As a developer deploying a Rust project,\n    10→I want codeharness to generate a multi-stage Dockerfile,\n    11→so that I get a minimal runtime image with just the compiled binary.\n    12→\n    13→## Acceptance Criteria\n    14→\n    15→1. **AC1:** Given a Rust project (stack = `'rust'`) without a Dockerfile, when `generateDockerfileTemplate('/project', 'rust')` is called, then it writes a Dockerfile and returns `ok({ path: '/project/Dockerfile', stack: 'rust' })` — NOT `'generic'` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    16→2. **AC2:** Given the generated Rust Dockerfile content, when inspected, then it contains a multi-stage build: a `FROM rust:1.82-slim AS builder` stage and a `FROM debian:bookworm-slim` runtime stage <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    17→3. **AC3:** Given the generated Rust Dockerfile content, when inspected, then the builder stage includes `cargo build --release` and the runtime stage uses `COPY --from=builder` to copy the compiled binary <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    18→4. **AC4:** Given the generated Rust Dockerfile content, when inspected, then the runtime stage installs `curl` and `jq` via `apt-get install`, runs as a non-root user, and includes `rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*` cache cleanup <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    19→5. **AC5:** Given a Rust project with an existing Dockerfile, when `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called, then it returns `fail('Dockerfile already exists')` <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    20→6. **AC6:** Given the generated Rust Dockerfile, when `validateDockerfile()` is called against it, then it passes all 6 rule categories with zero gaps <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    21→7. **AC7:** Given `codeharness init` runs on a Rust project without a Dockerfile, when the Dockerfile template generation phase executes, then it generates a Rust-specific Dockerfile (not generic) <!-- verification: integration-required -->\n    22→\n    23→## Tasks / Subtasks\n    24→\n    25→- [x] Task 1: Add `rustTemplate()` function to `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` (AC: #2, #3, #4)\n    26→  - [x]1.1 Create `rustTemplate(): string` returning a multi-stage Dockerfile string\n    27→  - [x]1.2 Builder stage: `FROM rust:1.82-slim AS builder`, `WORKDIR /build`, `COPY . .`, `RUN cargo build --release`\n    28→  - [x]1.3 Runtime stage: `FROM debian:bookworm-slim`, `apt-get install curl jq`, `rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*`, `COPY --from=builder /build/target/release/myapp /usr/local/bin/myapp`, `USER nobody`, `WORKDIR /workspace`\n    29→  - [x]1.4 Include inline section comments matching existing template style\n    30→- [x] Task 2: Add `'rust'` branch to `generateDockerfileTemplate()` (AC: #1)\n    31→  - [x]2.1 In the if/else chain (lines 99-108), add `else if (stack === 'rust')` BEFORE the generic fallthrough\n    32→  - [x]2.2 Set `content = rustTemplate()` and `resolvedStack = 'rust'`\n    33→- [x] Task 3: Update existing test that asserts `'rust'` maps to `'generic'` (AC: #1)\n    34→  - [x]3.1 In `src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-template.test.ts` line 167, the test `'generates generic Dockerfile when stack is unknown'` passes `'rust'` and expects `stack: 'generic'` — this MUST change\n    35→  - [x]3.2 Replace `'rust'` in that test with a different unknown stack (e.g., `'java'`) so the generic fallthrough test still works\n    36→- [x] Task 4: Add new `describe('generateDockerfileTemplate — rust')` test block (AC: #1, #2, #3, #4)\n    37→  - [x]4.1 Test: returns `stack: 'rust'` and correct path\n    38→  - [x]4.2 Test: contains `FROM rust:1.82-slim AS builder` and `FROM debian:bookworm-slim`\n    39→  - [x]4.3 Test: includes `cargo build --release` in builder stage\n    40→  - [x]4.4 Test: includes `COPY --from=builder` to copy compiled binary\n    41→  - [x]4.5 Test: includes `curl` and `jq` verification tools\n    42→  - [x]4.6 Test: includes `USER nobody` for non-root execution\n    43→  - [x]4.7 Test: includes apt cache cleanup (`rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*`)\n    44→  - [x]4.8 Test: includes inline section comments (`# Build`, `# System utilities`, `# Install`, `# Run as non-root`)\n    45→- [x] Task 5: Add Rust template to validation compliance tests (AC: #6)\n    46→  - [x]5.1 In the `describe('generated Dockerfiles pass validateDockerfile()')` block (line 273), add a `'rust template passes all 6 rule categories'` test\n    47→  - [x]5.2 Generate Rust template, feed content to `validateDockerfile()` via mocked `readFileSync`, assert `passed: true` and `gaps: []`\n    48→- [x] Task 6: Run full test suite — zero regressions\n    49→\n    50→## Dev Notes\n    51→\n    52→### Current Code Structure\n    53→\n    54→`src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` (119 lines) has three template functions and one generator:\n    55→- `nodejsTemplate()` L21 → single-stage, `FROM node:22-slim`, `npm install -g` from tarball\n    56→- `pythonTemplate()` L41 → single-stage, `FROM python:3.12-slim`, `pip install` from wheel\n    57→- `genericTemplate()` L59 → single-stage, `FROM node:22-slim`, placeholder\n    58→- `generateDockerfileTemplate(projectDir, stack)` L82 → if/else chain: `'nodejs'` → `'python'` → else (generic)\n    59→\n    60→Currently `'rust'` falls through to the `else` branch and produces a generic Dockerfile. After this story, it gets its own dedicated multi-stage template."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0171dfRPdau3d9vdSdBsjERK","session_id":"8e4c6a49-a8f5-4820-a234-101957ee0803","uuid":"cbe07c85-ad15-4afa-afa6-eeb7ac5c1bec","timestamp":"2026-03-23T07:34:06.435Z"}
