{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0171dfRPdau3d9vdSdBsjERK","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/8-7-rust-otlp-instrumentation.md`.\n\nSummary of what was done:\n\n- Rewrote story 8-7 in the full format matching completed stories (8-5, 8-6)\n- 8 ACs with verification tags: 7 `cli-verifiable`, 1 `integration-required` (AC8 -- full init pipeline on a Rust project)\n- 7 tasks with subtasks covering: `installRustOtlp()` function, `instrumentProject()` update, `.env.codeharness` endpoint writing, `configureAgent()` Rust skip, `templates/otlp/rust.md` creation, tests, and regression check\n- Dev Notes documenting current code state (placeholder Rust branch, existing Rust env var test, `configureAgent` missing Rust case), line budget concerns, and file boundaries\n- Did NOT modify `sprint-status.yaml`, did NOT run `git add` or `git commit`\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- The existing `configureAgent()` function has a bug for Rust: it falls through to the bottom where it unconditionally sets `agent_sdk: 'traceloop'` in state. This means Rust projects currently get `agent_sdk: 'traceloop'` even though there is no Rust Traceloop SDK. Task 4 of this story fixes it.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- AC2 references writing `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` to `.env.codeharness`, but the current codebase only writes `OTEL_SERVICE_NAME` there (the endpoint is stored in state YAML only). Task 3 adds this new behavior specifically for Rust, since Rust apps read env vars directly. This is a scope expansion beyond the original epic AC wording but is necessary to make AC2 testable.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- `otlp.ts` is already at 375 lines and will grow to ~410 lines, exceeding the 300-line NFR1 limit. The file was already over limit before this sprint. May need a follow-up refactor.\n- AC8 (`integration-required`